WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.790 --> 00:00:03.768
 Professor Ben
Polak: All right,

00:00:03.768 --> 00:00:06.495
so last time we did something I
think substantially harder than

00:00:06.495 --> 00:00:08.430
anything we've done in the class
so far.

00:00:08.430 --> 00:00:13.429
We looked at mixed strategies,
and in particular,

00:00:13.429 --> 00:00:17.700
we looked at mixed-strategy
equilibria.

00:00:17.700 --> 00:00:22.202
There was a big idea last time.
The big idea was if a player is

00:00:22.202 --> 00:00:26.392
playing a mixed strategy in
equilibrium, then every pure

00:00:26.392 --> 00:00:31.116
strategy in the mix--that's to
say every pure strategy on which

00:00:31.116 --> 00:00:35.002
they place some positive
weight--must also be a best

00:00:35.002 --> 00:00:38.660
response to what the other side
is doing.

00:00:38.660 --> 00:00:42.379
Then we used that trick.
We used it in this game here,

00:00:42.379 --> 00:00:46.264
to help us find Nash Equilibria
and the way it allowed us to

00:00:46.264 --> 00:00:49.360
find the Nash Equilibria is we
knew that if,

00:00:49.360 --> 00:00:52.149
in this case,
Venus Williams is mixing

00:00:52.149 --> 00:00:56.070
between left and right,
it must be this case that her

00:00:56.070 --> 00:01:00.896
payoff is equal to that of right
and we use that to find Serena's

00:01:00.896 --> 00:01:03.806
mix.
Conversely, since we knew that

00:01:03.806 --> 00:01:07.974
Serena is mixing again between l
and r, we knew she must be

00:01:07.974 --> 00:01:12.790
indifferent between l and r and
we used that to find Venus' mix.

00:01:12.790 --> 00:01:15.606
So I want to go back to this
example just for a few moments

00:01:15.606 --> 00:01:18.180
just to make one more point and
then we'll move on,

00:01:18.180 --> 00:01:20.415
but we'll still be talking
about mixed strategies

00:01:20.415 --> 00:01:23.140
throughout today.
So this was the mix that we

00:01:23.140 --> 00:01:26.957
found before we changed the
payoffs, we found that Venus'

00:01:26.957 --> 00:01:34.295
equilibrium mix was .7,
.3 and Serena's equilibrium mix

00:01:34.295 --> 00:01:38.198
was .6, .4.
And a reasonable question at

00:01:38.198 --> 00:01:41.383
this point would be,
how do we know that's really an

00:01:41.383 --> 00:01:43.550
equilibrium?
We kind of found it but we

00:01:43.550 --> 00:01:45.160
didn't kind of go back and
check.

00:01:45.160 --> 00:01:47.071
So what I want to do now is
actually do that,

00:01:47.071 --> 00:01:48.977
do that missing step.
We rushed it a bit last time

00:01:48.977 --> 00:01:50.629
because we wanted to get through
all the material.

00:01:50.629 --> 00:01:56.394
Let's actually check that in
fact P* is a best response to

00:01:56.394 --> 00:02:00.666
Q*.
So what I want to do is I want

00:02:00.666 --> 00:02:08.574
to check that Venus' mix P* is a
best response for Venus against

00:02:08.574 --> 00:02:13.007
Serena's mix Q*.
The way I'm going to do that is

00:02:13.007 --> 00:02:16.904
I'm going to look at payoffs
that Venus gets now she knows -

00:02:16.904 --> 00:02:20.669
or rather now we know
she's playing against Q*.

00:02:20.669 --> 00:02:23.009
So let's look at Venus'
payoffs..

00:02:23.009 --> 00:02:26.297
I'm going to figure out her
payoffs for L,

00:02:26.297 --> 00:02:29.985
her payoffs for R,
and also her payoff for what

00:02:29.985 --> 00:02:34.159
she's actually doing P*.
So Venus' payoffs,

00:02:34.159 --> 00:02:40.267
if she chooses L against Q*
then she gets--very similar to

00:02:40.267 --> 00:02:44.340
what we had on the board last
week,

00:02:44.340 --> 00:02:49.361
but now I'm going to put in
what Q* is explicitly--she gets

00:02:49.361 --> 00:02:56.039
50 times .6..
[This is Q* and this is 1-Q*.].

00:02:56.039 --> 00:03:07.875
So she gets 50 times .6 and 80
times 1 minus .6 which is .4,80

00:03:07.875 --> 00:03:11.335
times .4.
We can work this out,

00:03:11.335 --> 00:03:14.428
and I worked it out at home,
but if somebody has a

00:03:14.428 --> 00:03:16.890
calculator they can please check
me.

00:03:16.890 --> 00:03:24.120
I think this comes to .62.
Somebody should just check that.

00:03:24.120 --> 00:03:29.961
If Venus chose R--remember R
here means shooting to Serena's

00:03:29.961 --> 00:03:36.199
right, to Serena's forehand--if
she chose R then her payoffs are

00:03:36.199 --> 00:03:41.440
90 Q*.
So 90(.6) plus 20(1-Q*) so

00:03:41.440 --> 00:03:51.249
20(.4), so 90(.6) plus 20(.4),
and again I worked that out at

00:03:51.249 --> 00:03:59.750
home, and fortunately that also
comes out at .62.

00:03:59.750 --> 00:04:07.135
So what's Venus' payoff for P*?
We've got her payoff for both

00:04:07.135 --> 00:04:12.201
her pure strategies,
so her payoff from actually

00:04:12.201 --> 00:04:16.343
choosing P* is what?
Well, P* is .7,

00:04:16.343 --> 00:04:22.556
so .7 of the time she will
actually be playing L and when

00:04:22.556 --> 00:04:29.340
she plays L,
she'll get a payoff of .62,

00:04:29.340 --> 00:04:39.959
and .3 of the time she'll be
playing R, and once again,

00:04:39.959 --> 00:04:49.750
she'll be getting a payoff of
.62 and--do I have a calculator?

00:04:49.750 --> 00:04:51.476
Sorry, thank you.
So P* is .7,

00:04:51.476 --> 00:04:55.619
yes, you're absolutely right,
so this is P* and 1-P*,

00:04:55.619 --> 00:05:00.225
So let's make that clearer.
I'll show you what the

00:05:00.225 --> 00:05:03.850
equilibrium is but P* itself is
.7.

00:05:03.850 --> 00:05:06.754
So when Venus plays L with
probability of .7,

00:05:06.754 --> 00:05:10.715
then .7 of the time she'll get
the expected payoff of .62 and

00:05:10.715 --> 00:05:14.479
.3 of the time she'll get a
payoff again of .62 and that's

00:05:14.479 --> 00:05:17.780
the kind of math I don't have to
do at home,

00:05:17.780 --> 00:05:23.082
that's going to come out at .62.
Again, assuming my math is

00:05:23.082 --> 00:05:25.148
correct.
So all I've really done here is

00:05:25.148 --> 00:05:26.970
confirm what we did already last
time.

00:05:26.970 --> 00:05:33.502
We knew--we in fact chose
Serena's mix Q to make Venus

00:05:33.502 --> 00:05:39.267
indifferent between L and R.
And that's exactly what we

00:05:39.267 --> 00:05:43.959
found here, going left it's .62,
going right it gets .62 and

00:05:43.959 --> 00:05:47.327
hence P* gets .62.
But I claim we can now see

00:05:47.327 --> 00:05:51.134
something a little bit else.
We can now ask the question,

00:05:51.134 --> 00:05:53.389
is P* in fact the best
response?

00:05:53.389 --> 00:05:57.068
Well, for it not to be a best
response, for this not to be an

00:05:57.068 --> 00:06:00.747
equilibrium, there would have to
be some deviation that Venus

00:06:00.747 --> 00:06:04.120
could make that would make her
strictly better off.

00:06:04.120 --> 00:06:06.486
Let me repeat that.
If this were not an

00:06:06.486 --> 00:06:10.991
equilibrium, there would have to
be some deviation for Venus,

00:06:10.991 --> 00:06:14.220
that would make her strictly
better off.

00:06:14.220 --> 00:06:18.170
By playing P* she's getting a
return of .62.

00:06:18.170 --> 00:06:23.300
So one thing she could deviate
to, is playing L all the time.

00:06:23.300 --> 00:06:26.821
If she deviates to playing L
all the time,

00:06:26.821 --> 00:06:31.889
her payoff is still .62 so
she's not strictly better off.

00:06:31.889 --> 00:06:35.290
That's not a strictly
profitable deviation.

00:06:35.290 --> 00:06:39.300
Another thing she could deviate
to, is she could deviate to

00:06:39.300 --> 00:06:42.712
playing R.
If she deviates to playing R,

00:06:42.712 --> 00:06:46.820
her payoff will be .62.
Once again, she's not strictly

00:06:46.820 --> 00:06:49.711
better off: she's the same as
she was before,

00:06:49.711 --> 00:06:52.930
so that's not a strictly
profitable deviation.

00:06:52.930 --> 00:06:56.757
So what have I shown so far?
I've shown that P* is as good

00:06:56.757 --> 00:07:00.480
as playing L,
and P* is as good as playing R.

00:07:00.480 --> 00:07:02.639
In fact that's how we
constructed it.

00:07:02.639 --> 00:07:07.183
So deviating to L is not a
strictly profitable deviation

00:07:07.183 --> 00:07:12.139
and deviating to R is not a
strictly profitable deviation.

00:07:12.139 --> 00:07:15.578
But at this point,
somebody might ask and say,

00:07:15.578 --> 00:07:19.858
okay, you've shown me that
there's no way to deviate to a

00:07:19.858 --> 00:07:23.449
pure strategy in a strictly
profitable way,

00:07:23.449 --> 00:07:28.670
but how about deviating to
another mixed strategy?

00:07:28.670 --> 00:07:43.789
So, so far we've shown--we've
shown just up here--we can see

00:07:43.789 --> 00:07:56.602
that Venus has no strictly
profitable pure-strategy

00:07:56.602 --> 00:08:02.412
deviation.
She has no strictly profitable

00:08:02.412 --> 00:08:06.708
pure-strategy deviation because
each of her pure strategies

00:08:06.708 --> 00:08:10.560
yields the same payoff as did
her mixed strategy,

00:08:10.560 --> 00:08:14.483
yields the same as P*.
But how do we know that she

00:08:14.483 --> 00:08:18.920
doesn't have a mixed strategy
that would be strictly better?

00:08:18.920 --> 00:08:26.130
How do we know that?
Anybody?

00:08:26.130 --> 00:08:29.220
No hands going up;
oh, there was a hand up, good.

00:08:29.220 --> 00:08:32.411
Student: Any mix between
left and right will still yield

00:08:32.411 --> 00:08:34.909
.62.
Professor Ben Polak:

00:08:34.909 --> 00:08:39.208
Good, so any mix that Venus
deviates to, will be a mix

00:08:39.208 --> 00:08:43.707
between L and R,
and any mix between L and R

00:08:43.707 --> 00:08:50.279
will be a mix between .62 and
.62 and hence will yield .62.

00:08:50.279 --> 00:08:53.278
So we're going to use again,
this fact we developed last

00:08:53.278 --> 00:08:56.097
week.
The fact we developed last week

00:08:56.097 --> 00:09:00.186
was that any mixed strategy
yields a payoff that is a

00:09:00.186 --> 00:09:04.039
weighted average of the pure
strategy payoffs,

00:09:04.039 --> 00:09:06.570
the payoffs to the pure
strategies in the mix.

00:09:06.570 --> 00:09:09.274
Any mixed strategy yields a
payoff that is a weighted

00:09:09.274 --> 00:09:12.290
average of the payoff to the
pure strategies in the mix.

00:09:12.290 --> 00:09:16.125
That was our key fact last week.
So here if we've shown that

00:09:16.125 --> 00:09:19.947
there's no pure-strategy
deviation that's strictly

00:09:19.947 --> 00:09:23.253
profitable,
then there can't be any mixed

00:09:23.253 --> 00:09:26.840
strategy deviation that's
strictly profitable.

00:09:26.840 --> 00:09:29.156
Why?
Because the mixed strategy

00:09:29.156 --> 00:09:33.372
deviations must yield payoffs
that lie among the pure strategy

00:09:33.372 --> 00:09:36.310
deviations.
So this is a great fact for us.

00:09:36.310 --> 00:09:50.879
What's the lesson here?
The lesson is we only ever have

00:09:50.879 --> 00:10:12.900
to check for strictly profitable
pure-strategy deviations.

00:10:12.900 --> 00:10:13.960
That's a good job.
Why?

00:10:13.960 --> 00:10:17.316
Because if we had to check for
mixed strategy deviations one by

00:10:17.316 --> 00:10:20.123
one, we'd be here all night,
because there's an infinite

00:10:20.123 --> 00:10:22.139
number of possible
mixed-strategy deviations.

00:10:22.139 --> 00:10:23.848
But there aren't so many pure
strategy deviations we have to

00:10:23.848 --> 00:10:25.820
check.
Let's just repeat the idea.

00:10:25.820 --> 00:10:29.704
Suppose there isn't any
pure-strategy deviation that's

00:10:29.704 --> 00:10:34.027
profitable, then there can't be
any mixed strategy deviation

00:10:34.027 --> 00:10:37.639
that's profitable,
because the highest expected

00:10:37.639 --> 00:10:41.139
return you could ever get from a
mixed strategy,

00:10:41.139 --> 00:10:44.347
is one of the pure strategies
in the mix, and you've already

00:10:44.347 --> 00:10:46.740
checked that none of those are
profitable.

00:10:46.740 --> 00:10:50.705
So this simple idea,
the simple idea we developed

00:10:50.705 --> 00:10:55.000
last time, not only helps us to
find Nash Equilibria,

00:10:55.000 --> 00:10:58.470
but also to check for Nash
Equilibria.

00:10:58.470 --> 00:11:02.535
Now a lot of people I gathered
from feedback from sections were

00:11:02.535 --> 00:11:06.210
left pretty confused last time.
It's a hard idea.

00:11:06.210 --> 00:11:09.262
Actually I looked at the tape
over the weekend,

00:11:09.262 --> 00:11:12.049
I could see where it could be
confusing.

00:11:12.049 --> 00:11:13.957
But it's actually,
I think what's really confusing

00:11:13.957 --> 00:11:16.370
here--it wasn't so much--I think
it wasn't so much that I could

00:11:16.370 --> 00:11:18.549
have been clearer though I'm
sure I could have been.

00:11:18.549 --> 00:11:21.777
It's that this is really a hard
idea, this idea of mixed

00:11:21.777 --> 00:11:23.830
strategies.
So we're going to work on it

00:11:23.830 --> 00:11:26.457
again today, but I think one of
the ideas that gets people

00:11:26.457 --> 00:11:30.712
confused, is the following idea.
They say, look we found Venus'

00:11:30.712 --> 00:11:35.558
equilibrium mix by choosing a P
and a 1-P to make Serena

00:11:35.558 --> 00:11:38.854
indifferent.
We found Serena's equilibrium

00:11:38.854 --> 00:11:42.871
mix by finding a Q and a 1-Q to
make Venus indifferent and a

00:11:42.871 --> 00:11:46.139
natural question you hear people
ask then is,

00:11:46.139 --> 00:11:50.980
why is Venus "trying to make
Serena indifferent?"

00:11:50.980 --> 00:11:55.019
Why is Serena "trying to make
Venus indifferent?"

00:11:55.019 --> 00:11:57.330
That's not really the point
here.

00:11:57.330 --> 00:12:01.409
It isn't that Venus is trying
to make Serena indifferent.

00:12:01.409 --> 00:12:04.529
It's that in equilibrium,
she is going to make Serena

00:12:04.529 --> 00:12:06.804
indifferent.
It isn't her goal in life to

00:12:06.804 --> 00:12:09.928
make Serena indifferent between
l and r, and it isn't Serena's

00:12:09.928 --> 00:12:12.899
goal in life to make Venus
indifferent between L and R,

00:12:12.899 --> 00:12:16.981
but in equilibrium it ends up
that they make each other

00:12:16.981 --> 00:12:20.239
indifferent.
The way that we can see that is

00:12:20.239 --> 00:12:24.497
that if Venus puts--we said last
time it's repeated--if Venus

00:12:24.497 --> 00:12:27.588
puts too much weight,
more than .7 on L,

00:12:27.588 --> 00:12:31.289
then Serena just cheats to the
left all the time,

00:12:31.289 --> 00:12:34.759
and that can't possibly be an
equilibrium.

00:12:34.759 --> 00:12:37.928
And if Venus puts too much
weight on R, then Serena cheats

00:12:37.928 --> 00:12:41.320
to the right all the time and
that can't be an equilibrium.

00:12:41.320 --> 00:12:46.498
So it has to be that what Venus
is doing is going to make Serena

00:12:46.498 --> 00:12:49.539
exactly indifferent and vice
versa.

00:12:49.539 --> 00:12:52.960
Now let's see that idea in some
other applications.

00:12:52.960 --> 00:12:56.679
Let's talk about this a bit
before we move on.

00:12:56.679 --> 00:13:01.408
So it turns out that some very
natural applications for

00:13:01.408 --> 00:13:06.050
mixed-strategy equilibria arise
in games, in sport.

00:13:06.050 --> 00:13:10.657
So let's talk about a few now.
Can anybody suggest some other

00:13:10.657 --> 00:13:14.869
places where we see
randomization or at least mixed

00:13:14.869 --> 00:13:18.659
strategy in equilibria in
sporting events?

00:13:18.659 --> 00:13:22.570
Let me actually grab the mike
myself.

00:13:22.570 --> 00:13:26.895
Anybody here play football for
example, and we're talking

00:13:26.895 --> 00:13:29.984
American football now,
the gridiron game,

00:13:29.984 --> 00:13:33.149
not the civilized type.
Anyone play?

00:13:33.149 --> 00:13:34.570
Yes, so some of you play
football.

00:13:34.570 --> 00:13:40.450
So where is the mixing involved
in playing football?

00:13:40.450 --> 00:13:42.470
Where in equilibrium would we
expect to see mixed strategies?

00:13:42.470 --> 00:13:46.660
There's somebody down there can
we go on and get them.

00:13:46.660 --> 00:13:49.340
So shout it out.
Student: Running game

00:13:49.340 --> 00:13:50.673
and passing game.
Professor Ben Polak: All

00:13:50.673 --> 00:13:51.850
right, the running game and the
passing game.

00:13:51.850 --> 00:13:55.624
So a very simple idea whether
to run or whether to pass when

00:13:55.624 --> 00:13:59.206
you have the ball is likely to
end up as a mixed-strategy

00:13:59.206 --> 00:14:02.178
equilibrium.
The defense is also randomizing

00:14:02.178 --> 00:14:05.447
between, for example,
rushing the passer or playing a

00:14:05.447 --> 00:14:07.570
run defense.
Is that right--this is not

00:14:07.570 --> 00:14:09.932
exactly a game I know a lot
about, but I'm hoping I'm

00:14:09.932 --> 00:14:12.686
getting close enough here.
It couldn't possibly be a

00:14:12.686 --> 00:14:15.847
pure-strategy equilibrium,
other than very extreme parts

00:14:15.847 --> 00:14:18.046
of the game,
like at the end of the game

00:14:18.046 --> 00:14:20.968
perhaps, but for most of the
game, it's very unlikely to end

00:14:20.968 --> 00:14:22.799
up as a pure-strategy
equilibrium.

00:14:22.799 --> 00:14:25.363
Much more likely that the
offense is mixing between

00:14:25.363 --> 00:14:27.772
passing and running,
and for that matter between

00:14:27.772 --> 00:14:31.151
going to the left,
going to the right and going to

00:14:31.151 --> 00:14:35.437
the center, and the defense is
also mixing between--over its

00:14:35.437 --> 00:14:38.610
types of defense.
So we see that--for those

00:14:38.610 --> 00:14:41.981
people who were watching
yesterday--we see that in

00:14:41.981 --> 00:14:46.174
football games.
Where do we see it else in

00:14:46.174 --> 00:14:50.559
sport, some other sports?
I can't have a room full of

