00:45:27.520 --> 00:45:33.840
Why are they doing this?
This leads us to think about a

00:45:33.840 --> 00:45:37.445
second interpretation for what
we think mixed strategy

00:45:37.445 --> 00:45:40.655
equilibria are.
Rather than thinking of them

00:45:40.655 --> 00:45:44.412
literally as randomizing,
it's probably better in this

00:45:44.412 --> 00:45:47.389
case to think about the
following idea.

00:45:47.389 --> 00:45:53.074
We need to think about David's
mixture as being a statement

00:45:53.074 --> 00:45:57.679
about what Nina believes David's
going to do.

00:45:57.679 --> 00:46:01.030
David may not be literally
randomizing.

00:46:01.030 --> 00:46:05.009
But his mixture Q,
1--Q, we could think of as

00:46:05.009 --> 00:46:09.260
Nina's belief about what David's
going to do.

00:46:09.260 --> 00:46:14.329
Conversely, Nina may not
literally be randomizing.

00:46:14.329 --> 00:46:19.049
But her P, 1 - P,
we could think of as David's

00:46:19.049 --> 00:46:23.139
belief about what Nina's going
to do.

00:46:23.139 --> 00:46:28.542
And what we've done is we've
found the beliefs such that

00:46:28.542 --> 00:46:34.239
these players are exactly
indifferent over what they do.

00:46:34.239 --> 00:46:37.790
We found the beliefs for David
over what Nina's going to do,

00:46:37.790 --> 00:46:41.099
such that David doesn't really
quite know what to do.

00:46:41.099 --> 00:46:44.654
And we found the beliefs that
Nina holds about what David's

00:46:44.654 --> 00:46:48.270
going to do such that Nina
doesn't quite know what to do.

00:46:48.270 --> 00:46:54.270
That make sense?
So it's probably better here to

00:46:54.270 --> 00:46:58.954
think about this not as people
literally randomizing but these

00:46:58.954 --> 00:47:02.870
mixed strategies being a
statement about what people

00:47:02.870 --> 00:47:06.742
believe in equilibrium.
We'll come back and look at

00:47:06.742 --> 00:47:10.380
this game some more later on,
so our couple I'm afraid are

00:47:10.380 --> 00:47:14.156
not quite out of the woods yet.
But I want to spend the rest of

00:47:14.156 --> 00:47:17.264
today looking at yet another
interpretation of mixed strategy

00:47:17.264 --> 00:47:20.035
equilibria.
So, so far we have two,

00:47:20.035 --> 00:47:23.769
we have people are literally
randomizing.

00:47:23.769 --> 00:47:27.004
We have thinking of these as
expressions about what people

00:47:27.004 --> 00:47:30.182
believe in equilibrium rather
than what they're literally

00:47:30.182 --> 00:47:38.886
doing.
And now I'm going to give you a

00:47:38.886 --> 00:47:50.249
third interpretation.
So for now we can get rid of

00:47:50.249 --> 00:47:58.597
the Venus and Serena game.
So to motivate this third idea

00:47:58.597 --> 00:48:01.949
I want to think about tax
audits.

00:48:01.949 --> 00:48:04.031
So none of you here have ever,
probably ever,

00:48:04.031 --> 00:48:06.727
had to fill out a tax form,
except for the fact that there

00:48:06.727 --> 00:48:09.139
seems to be a lot of parents in
the room today,

00:48:09.139 --> 00:48:11.559
is it parents weekend,
is that what's going on?

00:48:11.559 --> 00:48:13.110
So where are the parents in the
room?

00:48:13.110 --> 00:48:16.059
Wave your arms in the air if
you're a parent here.

00:48:16.059 --> 00:48:19.149
So at least these guys at
probably some point in their

00:48:19.149 --> 00:48:21.931
life filled out a tax form.
So come tax day,

00:48:21.931 --> 00:48:25.954
the parents in the room face a
choice, and the choice is are

00:48:25.954 --> 00:48:30.115
they going to honestly fill out
their taxes, or are they going

00:48:30.115 --> 00:48:33.642
to cheat?
I'm not going to ask them what

00:48:33.642 --> 00:48:38.102
they, well maybe I will,
but for now I won't ask them

00:48:38.102 --> 00:48:41.519
what they did.
So they can choose one of two

00:48:41.519 --> 00:48:44.090
things.
They can choose to pay their

00:48:44.090 --> 00:48:47.570
taxes honestly--we'll call that
H--or to cheat.

00:48:47.570 --> 00:48:54.000
This is the tax payer,
the parent.

00:48:54.000 --> 00:48:57.694
And at the same time the audit
office, the auditor,

00:48:57.694 --> 00:49:01.240
has to make a choice,
and the auditor's choice is

00:49:01.240 --> 00:49:05.821
whether to audit you or not and
it's not literally true because

00:49:05.821 --> 00:49:10.255
literally the auditor can wait
until your tax return comes in

00:49:10.255 --> 00:49:13.579
and then decide whether to audit
you.

00:49:13.579 --> 00:49:16.990
But for now let's think of
these choices being made

00:49:16.990 --> 00:49:20.127
simultaneously,
and we'll see why that makes it

00:49:20.127 --> 00:49:24.606
more interesting.
So let me put down some payoffs

00:49:24.606 --> 00:49:36.410
here and then I'll explain them.
So 2,0, 4, -10,4, 0 and 0,4.

00:49:36.410 --> 00:49:39.257
So how do we interpret this?
Let's look at the auditor's

00:49:39.257 --> 00:49:42.829
payoffs first of all.
So the auditor is very happy

00:49:42.829 --> 00:49:47.717
not having to audit your parents
and having your parents pay

00:49:47.717 --> 00:49:51.280
taxes, so we'll give that a
payoff of 4.

00:49:51.280 --> 00:49:53.325
It'll turn out,
in this game,

00:49:53.325 --> 00:49:57.417
we've decided in the payoffs,
that the auditor is equally

00:49:57.417 --> 00:50:01.581
happy if she actually audits
your parents in the year that

00:50:01.581 --> 00:50:05.354
they cheated.
We'll say that makes the

00:50:05.354 --> 00:50:10.627
auditor equally happy.
Now the auditor is not so happy

00:50:10.627 --> 00:50:16.410
if she audits your parents when
they're honest because audits

00:50:16.410 --> 00:50:20.882
are costly.
The auditor is really unhappy

00:50:20.882 --> 00:50:26.050
if she fails to audit when the
parents cheated.

00:50:26.050 --> 00:50:28.138
Let's look at the--I keep
wanting to call them parents--I

00:50:28.138 --> 00:50:29.927
should stop calling them
parents, let's call them

00:50:29.927 --> 00:50:31.644
taxpayers.
So for the taxpayers,

00:50:31.644 --> 00:50:35.281
what are their payoffs?
Well we'll normalize things,

00:50:35.281 --> 00:50:39.500
so if they're honest we'll give
them a payoff of 0.

00:50:39.500 --> 00:50:42.053
That means they correctly fill
in their tax form and pay what

00:50:42.053 --> 00:50:44.815
they're supposed to pay,
but if they can conceal some of

00:50:44.815 --> 00:50:47.059
their income,
they pretend to have whatever

00:50:47.059 --> 00:50:48.673
it is,
a third child,

00:50:48.673 --> 00:50:52.719
then they might be in trouble
if they're audited.

00:50:52.719 --> 00:50:56.056
If they're audited they're
going to have to pay a big fine,

00:50:56.056 --> 00:50:58.300
maybe even go to jail,
so that's -10.

00:50:58.300 --> 00:51:02.194
Of course if they're not
audited they get to keep a chunk

00:51:02.194 --> 00:51:06.232
of money so we'll call that 4.
Everyone understand the basic

00:51:06.232 --> 00:51:08.643
idea of this game?
In reality, we could add more

00:51:08.643 --> 00:51:10.372
complications,
we could think of different

00:51:10.372 --> 00:51:13.085
ways to cheat on your taxes,
but I don't want to give

00:51:13.085 --> 00:51:15.780
tutorials on how to cheat on
your taxes here.

00:51:15.780 --> 00:51:19.448
So it's not going to take long
staring at this game to figure

00:51:19.448 --> 00:51:22.689
out that there are no pure
strategy equilibria in this

00:51:22.689 --> 00:51:24.681
game.
Let's just do that,

00:51:24.681 --> 00:51:29.155
so from the taxpayer's point of
view, if they're going to be

00:51:29.155 --> 00:51:32.415
audited,
then they'd rather pay their

00:51:32.415 --> 00:51:36.313
taxes than not,
and if they're not going to be

00:51:36.313 --> 00:51:41.769
audited then according to these
payoffs they'd rather cheat.

00:51:41.769 --> 00:51:45.095
From the auditor's point of
view, if they knew everyone was

00:51:45.095 --> 00:51:48.265
going to pay taxes,
then they wouldn't bother

00:51:48.265 --> 00:51:52.590
auditing and if they knew
everyone was going to cheat,

00:51:52.590 --> 00:51:59.233
then they'd of course audit.
So you can quickly see that

00:51:59.233 --> 00:52:02.828
there's no box in which the best
responses coincide,

00:52:02.828 --> 00:52:05.929
there's no pure strategy Nash
Equilibria.

00:52:05.929 --> 00:52:08.754
For those people who are
thinking this is seeming other

00:52:08.754 --> 00:52:11.840
worldly, you will have to pay
taxes in a couple of years,

00:52:11.840 --> 00:52:16.829
and trust me your parents are
paying taxes now.

00:52:16.829 --> 00:52:20.139
So what we want to do here is
we're going to solve out and

00:52:20.139 --> 00:52:22.230
find a mixed strategy
equilibrium,

00:52:22.230 --> 00:52:25.320
but we're going to give it a
different interpretation to the

00:52:25.320 --> 00:52:27.659
equilibria we found so far.
But the basic,

00:52:27.659 --> 00:52:31.846
initial exercise is what?
We're going to find--we're

00:52:31.846 --> 00:52:36.360
going to try and find the
equilibrium here.

00:52:36.360 --> 00:52:41.283
So to find the Nash Equilibrium
here we know it's going to be

00:52:41.283 --> 00:52:44.509
mixed.
So to find the probability with

00:52:44.509 --> 00:52:49.151
which taxpayers pay their
taxes--and let me already start

00:52:49.151 --> 00:52:54.207
getting ahead of myself and just
say to find the proportion of

00:52:54.207 --> 00:52:59.429
taxpayers who are going to pay
their taxes--what do we do?

00:52:59.429 --> 00:53:03.732
What must be true of that
equilibrium proportion Q of

00:53:03.732 --> 00:53:08.790
taxpayers who pay their taxes?
How am I going to find that Q?

00:53:08.790 --> 00:53:13.299
Shout it out somebody.
Yeah look at the auditor's

00:53:13.299 --> 00:53:19.179
payoffs.
So from the auditor's point of

00:53:19.179 --> 00:53:29.444
view, if the auditor audits,
their payoff is 2Q plus 4(1-Q)

00:53:29.444 --> 00:53:39.710
and if they don't audit their
payoff is 4Q plus 0(1-Q).

00:53:39.710 --> 00:53:44.573
Everyone see how I do this,
this is 2Q plus 4(1-Q) and this

00:53:44.573 --> 00:53:50.183
is 4Q plus 0(1-Q).
And if indeed the auditor is

00:53:50.183 --> 00:53:54.960
mixing, then these must be
equal.

00:53:54.960 --> 00:54:06.053
And if they're equal,
let's just do a little bit of

00:54:06.053 --> 00:54:19.366
algebra here and we'll find that
2Q equals 4(1-Q) so Q equals

00:54:19.366 --> 00:54:26.353
2/3, is that right?
So our claim is to make the

00:54:26.353 --> 00:54:30.610
auditor exactly indifferent
between whether to audit or not,

00:54:30.610 --> 00:54:35.819
it must be the case that 2/3 of
the parents of the kids in the

00:54:35.819 --> 00:54:40.260
room, are going to be paying
their taxes honestly,

00:54:40.260 --> 00:54:43.073
which means 1/3 aren't,
which is kind of worrying,

00:54:43.073 --> 00:54:45.624
but never mind.
Let's have a look at the

00:54:45.624 --> 00:54:50.320
taxpayer.
To find, sorry.

00:54:50.320 --> 00:54:52.550
We found the taxpayer,
we found the proportion of

00:54:52.550 --> 00:54:55.291
taxpayers who are paying their
taxes, now I want to find out

00:54:55.291 --> 00:54:57.010
the probability of being
audited.

00:54:57.010 --> 00:55:01.458
How do I figure out the
equilibrium probability of being

00:55:01.458 --> 00:55:05.313
audited in this model?
How do I work out the

00:55:05.313 --> 00:55:09.140
equilibrium probability of being
audited?

00:55:09.140 --> 00:55:13.560
Shout it out.
So the equilibrium probability

00:55:13.560 --> 00:55:16.514
of being audited are going to
use P and 1-P,

00:55:16.514 --> 00:55:20.087
so P is going to be the
probability of being audited,

00:55:20.087 --> 00:55:23.005
how do I find P?
Yeah, I'm going to look at the

00:55:23.005 --> 00:55:29.334
taxpayer's payoffs.
So from the taxpayer's point of

00:55:29.334 --> 00:55:40.024
view, if the taxpayer pays their
taxes, their payoff is just 0,

00:55:40.024 --> 00:55:49.679
and if they cheat they're
payoff is -10P plus 4(1-P).

00:55:49.679 --> 00:55:53.639
And if indeed the taxpayers are
mixing--or in other words,

00:55:53.639 --> 00:55:57.530
we are saying that not all
taxpayers are cheating and not

00:55:57.530 --> 00:56:01.420
all taxpayers are honestly
paying their taxes--then these

00:56:01.420 --> 00:56:07.131
must be equal.
So if these are equal I'm going

00:56:07.131 --> 00:56:14.518
to get 4P equals 14--no it
didn't-- I'm going to get 4

00:56:14.518 --> 00:56:18.000
equals 14P,
let's try again,

00:56:18.000 --> 00:56:21.540
4 equals 14P,
that was a bit worrying,

00:56:21.540 --> 00:56:25.559
4 equals 14P,
which is the same as saying P

00:56:25.559 --> 00:56:29.626
equals 2/7.
If somebody can just check my

00:56:29.626 --> 00:56:34.789
algebra I think that's right.
So my claim is that the

00:56:34.789 --> 00:56:41.634
equilibrium here is for 2/3 of
the taxpayers to pay their taxes

00:56:41.634 --> 00:56:45.057
and for the audits,
the auditor,

00:56:45.057 --> 00:56:49.902
to audit 2/7 of the time.
Now we could go back in here

00:56:49.902 --> 00:56:52.639
and we could check,
I could do what I did before,

00:56:52.639 --> 00:56:56.397
I could plug the Ps and Qs in
here and check that in fact this

00:56:56.397 --> 00:56:59.920
is an equilibrium,
but trust me that I've done

00:56:59.920 --> 00:57:04.576
that, trust me that it's okay.
So here we have an equilibrium,

00:57:04.576 --> 00:57:06.800
let's just write down what it
is.

00:57:06.800 --> 00:57:12.259
From the auditor's point of
view it is that they audit 2/7

00:57:12.259 --> 00:57:16.090
of the time, or 2/7 of the
population,

00:57:16.090 --> 00:57:21.511
and from the taxpayers' point
of view, it's that they pay

00:57:21.511 --> 00:57:27.030
their taxes honestly 2/3 of the
time and not otherwise.

00:57:27.030 --> 00:57:31.150
Now without focusing too much
on these exact numbers for a

00:57:31.150 --> 00:57:35.054
second, I want to focus first
for a minute on how do we

00:57:35.054 --> 00:57:38.380
interpret this mixed strategy
equilibrium.

00:57:38.380 --> 00:57:41.862
So from the point of view of
the auditor we're really back

00:57:41.862 --> 00:57:45.589
where we were before with the
base stealer or the person who's

00:57:45.589 --> 00:57:47.849
searching baggage at the
airport.

00:57:47.849 --> 00:57:53.199
We could think of the auditor
literally as randomizing.

00:57:53.199 --> 00:57:54.730
In fact, there's some truth to
that.

00:57:54.730 --> 00:57:59.030
It actually is the case that by
law, that the auditor's

00:57:59.030 --> 00:58:03.409
literally have to randomize.
So this 2/7,5/7 this has the

00:58:03.409 --> 00:58:06.110
same interpretation as we had
before.

00:58:06.110 --> 00:58:11.550
This is really a randomization.
But this 2/3,1/3 has a

00:58:11.550 --> 00:58:15.233
different interpretation and a
potentially exciting

00:58:15.233 --> 00:58:18.688
interpretation.
It isn't that we think that

00:58:18.688 --> 00:58:23.341
your parents get to tax day,
work out what their taxes would

00:58:23.341 --> 00:58:26.443
be and then toss a coin.
They may be doing that,

00:58:26.443 --> 00:58:28.770
I'm looking at the parents and
I don't think that's what

00:58:28.770 --> 00:58:31.005
they're doing.
The interpretation here is that

00:58:31.005 --> 00:58:33.741
the parents, some parents are
paying their taxes and some

00:58:33.741 --> 00:58:35.550
parents aren't paying their
taxes.

00:58:35.550 --> 00:58:38.446
There's a lot of parents out
there, a lot of potential

00:58:38.446 --> 00:58:40.360
taxpayers, and in the
population,

00:58:40.360 --> 00:58:43.329
in equilibrium,
if these numbers were true,

00:58:43.329 --> 00:58:47.500
2/3, of parents would be paying
their taxes and 1/3 would be

00:58:47.500 --> 00:58:52.174
cheating.
So this is a randomization by a

00:58:52.174 --> 00:58:58.110
player, and this is a mixture in
the population.

00:58:58.110 --> 00:59:01.372
The new interpretation here is,
we could think of the mixed

00:59:01.372 --> 00:59:03.510
strategy not as players
randomizing,

00:59:03.510 --> 00:59:06.433
but as a mix in a large
population of which some people

00:59:06.433 --> 00:59:09.789
are doing one thing and the
other group are doing the other.

00:59:09.789 --> 00:59:14.949
It's a proportion of people
paying taxes.

00:59:14.949 --> 00:59:17.804
So I don't know if this 2/3,1/3
is an accurate number for the

00:59:17.804 --> 00:59:19.777
U.S.
It's probably not very far off

00:59:19.777 --> 00:59:22.403
actually.
For Italy I'm ashamed to say

00:59:22.403 --> 00:59:26.309
the number of people who pay
taxes is more like 40%,

00:59:26.309 --> 00:59:29.749
maybe even lower now,
and there are countries I think

00:59:29.749 --> 00:59:32.800
where it gets as high as 90%.
I think the U.S.

00:59:32.800 --> 00:59:39.000
rate when they end up auditing
is a little higher than this but

00:59:39.000 --> 00:59:42.496
not much.
So again, we're going to think

00:59:42.496 --> 00:59:46.809
of this not as randomization but
as a prediction of the

00:59:46.809 --> 00:59:51.441
proportion of American taxpayers
who are going to pay their

00:59:51.441 --> 00:59:54.565
taxes.
Now, I want to use this example

00:59:54.565 --> 00:59:58.188
in the time we have left,
to actually think about a

00:59:58.188 --> 01:00:06.303
policy experiment.
So let's put this up somewhere

01:00:06.303 --> 01:00:12.307
we can see it.
Let's think about a new tax

01:00:12.307 --> 01:00:14.887
policy.
So suppose that Congress gets

01:00:14.887 --> 01:00:18.258
fed up with all these newspaper
reports about how 2/3 of

01:00:18.258 --> 01:00:22.119
American's don't pay their taxes
or whatever the true proportion

01:00:22.119 --> 01:00:23.443
is,
I think it's actually a little

01:00:23.443 --> 01:00:26.799
higher than that but never mind.
They get fed up with all these

01:00:26.799 --> 01:00:29.809
reports and they say,
this isn't fair,

01:00:29.809 --> 01:00:34.770
we should make people pay their
taxes so we're going to change

01:00:34.770 --> 01:00:39.162
the law and instead of
paying--instead of being in jail

01:00:39.162 --> 01:00:43.712
for ten years,
or the equivalent of a fine of

01:00:43.712 --> 01:00:49.301
-10 if you're caught cheating,
we're going to raise the fine

01:00:49.301 --> 01:00:53.469
or the time in jail so that it's
now -20.

01:00:53.469 --> 01:01:01.330
So the policy experiment is
let's raise the fine--to fine

01:01:01.330 --> 01:01:10.032
the cheating--to -20 and the aim
of this policy is try to deter

01:01:10.032 --> 01:01:15.819
cheating, right?
It seems a plausible thing for

01:01:15.819 --> 01:01:23.427
a government to want to do.
Let's redraw the matrix,

01:01:23.427 --> 01:01:31.271
so here's the game - 2,0,
4, -20,4, 0,0,

01:01:31.271 --> 01:01:41.530
4 audit, not audit and pay
honestly or cheating.

01:01:41.530 --> 01:01:44.770
So here's our new payoffs and
let's ask the question,

01:01:44.770 --> 01:01:48.467
with this new fine in place,
now we've raised the fine,

01:01:48.467 --> 01:01:52.543
to being caught not paying your
taxes, in the long run once

01:01:52.543 --> 01:01:56.760
things have worked their way
back into equilibrium again,

01:01:56.760 --> 01:02:01.095
after a few years,
do we expect American taxpaying

01:02:01.095 --> 01:02:04.280
compliance to go up or to go
down,

01:02:04.280 --> 01:02:07.701
or what do we expect?
What do we think is going to

01:02:07.701 --> 01:02:10.729
happen?
So who thinks it's going to go

01:02:10.729 --> 01:02:13.055
up?
Who thinks it's going to go

01:02:13.055 --> 01:02:15.427
down?
Who thinks it's going to say

01:02:15.427 --> 01:02:17.679
the same?
Who's abstaining here?

01:02:17.679 --> 01:02:18.860
I notice the parents are
abstaining.

01:02:18.860 --> 01:02:20.080
u're not really meant to
abstain.

01:02:20.080 --> 01:02:23.814
You have to vote here.
Well how are we going to figure

01:02:23.814 --> 01:02:25.792
this out?
How are we going to figure out

01:02:25.792 --> 01:02:27.810
what's going to happen to
compliance?

01:02:27.810 --> 01:02:39.869
What happens to tax compliance?
Tax compliance,

01:02:39.869 --> 01:02:45.061
remember that was our P--no it
wasn't, sorry,

01:02:45.061 --> 01:02:49.227
it was our Q.
The only way we're going to

01:02:49.227 --> 01:02:54.374
figure this out is to work out,
so let's work out the new Q in

01:02:54.374 --> 01:02:56.370
equilibrium.
Let's do this,

01:02:56.370 --> 01:02:59.029
so to find out the new Q in
equilibrium, once again,

01:02:59.029 --> 01:03:01.949
we're going to have to look at
the auditor's payoffs,

01:03:01.949 --> 01:03:08.362
and the auditor's payoffs if
they audit, they're going to get

01:03:08.362 --> 01:03:14.660
2Q plus 4(1-Q),
and if they don't audit they're

01:03:14.660 --> 01:03:21.742
going to get 4Q plus 0(1-Q),
and if the auditor is

01:03:21.742 --> 01:03:24.962
indifferent,
if they're mixing,

01:03:24.962 --> 01:03:27.769
it must still be the case that
these are equal.

01:03:27.769 --> 01:03:31.052
And now I want to ask you a
question, where have you seen

01:03:31.052 --> 01:03:33.826
that equation before?
Yeah, it's still there right,

01:03:33.826 --> 01:03:38.165
I didn't delete it.
It's the same equation that

01:03:38.165 --> 01:03:41.909
sits up there.
Is that right?

01:03:41.909 --> 01:03:45.874
From the auditor's point of
view, given the payoffs to the

01:03:45.874 --> 01:03:50.257
auditors nothing has changed,
so the tax compliance rate that

01:03:50.257 --> 01:03:54.065
makes the auditor exactly
indifferent between auditing

01:03:54.065 --> 01:03:57.369
your parents and not auditing
your parents,

01:03:57.369 --> 01:04:03.570
is still exactly the same as it
was before at 2/3.

01:04:03.570 --> 01:04:09.456
In equilibrium,
tax compliance hasn't changed

01:04:09.456 --> 01:04:12.751
at all.
Let me say that again,

01:04:12.751 --> 01:04:17.978
the policy was we're going to
double the fines for being

01:04:17.978 --> 01:04:22.921
caught cheating and in
equilibrium it made absolutely

01:04:22.921 --> 01:04:29.480
no difference whatsoever to the
equilibrium tax compliance rate.

01:04:29.480 --> 01:04:32.949
Now why did it make no
difference?

01:04:32.949 --> 01:04:35.465
Well let's have a techie answer
and then a better,

01:04:35.465 --> 01:04:39.337
a more intuitive answer.
The techie answer is this,

01:04:39.337 --> 01:04:44.315
what determines the equilibrium
tax compliance rate,

01:04:44.315 --> 01:04:50.073
what determines the equilibrium
mix for the column player is

01:04:50.073 --> 01:04:55.230
what?
Is the row's payoffs.

01:04:55.230 --> 01:04:58.806
What determines the equilibrium
mix for the column player are

01:04:58.806 --> 01:05:01.309
the row's payoffs--row player's
payoffs.

01:05:01.309 --> 01:05:05.104
We didn't change the row
player's payoffs,

01:05:05.104 --> 01:05:10.194
so we're not going to change
the equilibrium mix for the

01:05:10.194 --> 01:05:13.814
column player.
Say again, we changed one of

01:05:13.814 --> 01:05:17.722
the payoffs for the column
player but the column player's

01:05:17.722 --> 01:05:21.699
equilibrium mix depends on the
row player's payoffs and we

01:05:21.699 --> 01:05:24.909
haven't changed the row player's
payoffs,

01:05:24.909 --> 01:05:28.963
so we won't change the
equilibrium compliance rate,

01:05:28.963 --> 01:05:32.450
the equilibrium mix by the
column player.

01:05:32.450 --> 01:05:37.675
What will have changed here?
What will have changed in the

01:05:37.675 --> 01:05:40.074
new equilibrium?
So we've pretty much

01:05:40.074 --> 01:05:42.664
established that people are
cheating as much as they were

01:05:42.664 --> 01:05:45.320
before in equilibrium.
Rahul, can I get Henry here?

01:05:45.320 --> 01:05:47.050
Student: Probability has
changed.

01:05:47.050 --> 01:05:47.590
Professor Ben Polak: Say
again.

01:05:47.590 --> 01:05:48.949
Student: The probability
of audit would have changed.

01:05:48.949 --> 01:05:50.384
Professor Ben Polak: The
probability of audit will have

01:05:50.384 --> 01:05:52.640
changed.
What's going to change is not

01:05:52.640 --> 01:05:55.566
the Q but the P,
the probability with which

01:05:55.566 --> 01:05:59.119
you're audited is going to
change in this model.

01:05:59.119 --> 01:06:02.401
Let's just check it,
to find the new P,

01:06:02.401 --> 01:06:06.460
I need to look at the
taxpayer's payoffs and the

01:06:06.460 --> 01:06:10.962
taxpayer's payoffs are now 0,
–sorry,

01:06:10.962 --> 01:06:17.062
if they pay their taxes
honestly then they get 0,

01:06:17.062 --> 01:06:24.561
and if they cheat they get -20
with probability P and 4 with

01:06:24.561 --> 01:06:27.986
probability 1-P.
If they're mixing,

01:06:27.986 --> 01:06:30.129
if some of them are paying and
some of them are not,

01:06:30.129 --> 01:06:35.664
this must be the same,
and I'm being more careful than

01:06:35.664 --> 01:06:43.331
I was last time I hope,
this gives me 24 P is equal to

01:06:43.331 --> 01:06:50.916
4 or P equals 1/6.
So the audit rate has gone down

01:06:50.916 --> 01:06:54.864
from 2/7 to 1/6.
I'm guessing that probably

01:06:54.864 --> 01:06:58.222
wasn't the goal of the policy
although it isn't necessarily a

01:06:58.222 --> 01:07:00.276
bad thing.
There is some benefit for

01:07:00.276 --> 01:07:02.345
society here,
because audits are costly,

01:07:02.345 --> 01:07:05.210
both to do for the auditor and
they're unpleasant to be

01:07:05.210 --> 01:07:08.348
audited,
so the fact that we've managed

01:07:08.348 --> 01:07:13.000
to lower the audit rate from 2/7
to 1/6 is a good thing,

01:07:13.000 --> 01:07:22.820
but we didn't manage to raise
the compliance rate.

01:07:22.820 --> 01:07:25.556
So I don't want to take this
model too literally,

01:07:25.556 --> 01:07:28.657
because it's just a toy model,
but nevertheless,

01:07:28.657 --> 01:07:32.639
let's try and draw out some
lessons from this model.

01:07:32.639 --> 01:07:37.364
So here what we did was we
changed the payoff to cheating,

01:07:37.364 --> 01:07:41.149
we made it worse.
But a different kind of change

01:07:41.149 --> 01:07:45.127
is we could have changed,
sorry,- we changed the payoff

01:07:45.127 --> 01:07:48.000
negatively to being caught
cheating.

01:07:48.000 --> 01:07:51.622
But a different change we could
have done is we could have left

01:07:51.622 --> 01:07:54.776
the -10 in place and we could
have raised the payoff to

01:07:54.776 --> 01:07:59.348
cheating and not getting caught.
We could have left this 10 in

01:07:59.348 --> 01:08:03.690
place and changed this 4 let's
say to a 6 or an 8.

01:08:03.690 --> 01:08:08.019
We've increased the benefits to
cheating if you're not caught.

01:08:08.019 --> 01:08:13.230
What would that have done in
equilibrium?

01:08:13.230 --> 01:08:16.916
So I claim, once again,
that would have done nothing in

01:08:16.916 --> 01:08:21.149
equilibrium to the probability
of people paying their taxes,

01:08:21.149 --> 01:08:25.149
but that would have done what
to the audit rate?

01:08:25.149 --> 01:08:28.142
The audit rate would have gone
up, the equilibrium audit rate

01:08:28.142 --> 01:08:31.390
would have gone up.
Let's tell that story a second.

01:08:31.390 --> 01:08:33.928
So rich people,
people who are well paid,

01:08:33.928 --> 01:08:37.800
have a little bit more to gain
from cheating on their taxes if

01:08:37.800 --> 01:08:41.310
they're not caught,
there's more money at stake.

01:08:41.310 --> 01:08:44.095
So my colleagues who are
finance professors in the

01:08:44.095 --> 01:08:47.789
business school have more money
on their tax returns than I do,

01:08:47.789 --> 01:08:52.170
so in principle,
they gain more if they cheat.

01:08:52.170 --> 01:08:56.909
Does that mean that they cheat
more than me in equilibrium?

01:08:56.909 --> 01:08:58.425
No, it doesn't mean that they
cheat more than me in

01:08:58.425 --> 01:09:01.319
equilibrium.
What does it mean?

01:09:01.319 --> 01:09:04.909
It means they get audited more
often.

01:09:04.909 --> 01:09:07.482
In equilibrium,
richer people aren't

01:09:07.482 --> 01:09:11.671
necessarily going to cheat more,
but they are going to get

01:09:11.671 --> 01:09:14.170
audited more,
and that's true.

01:09:14.170 --> 01:09:17.617
The federal audit rates are
designed so they audit the rich

01:09:17.617 --> 01:09:20.738
more than they audit the poor.
Again, it's not because they

01:09:20.738 --> 01:09:23.218
think the rich are inherently
less honest, or the poor are

01:09:23.218 --> 01:09:25.279
inherently more honest,
or anything like that,

01:09:25.279 --> 01:09:27.814
it's simply that the gains to
cheating and not getting caught

01:09:27.814 --> 01:09:32.039
are bigger if you're rich,
so you need to audit more to

01:09:32.039 --> 01:09:37.525
push back into equilibrium.
Now, suppose we did in fact

01:09:37.525 --> 01:09:42.312
want to use the policy of
raising fines to push down,

01:09:42.312 --> 01:09:47.560
to push up the compliance rate,
to push down cheating.

01:09:47.560 --> 01:09:52.317
How would we change the law?
Suppose we want to raise the

01:09:52.317 --> 01:09:55.192
fines for cheating,
we don't like people cheating

01:09:55.192 --> 01:09:58.447
so we raise the fines,
but we're worried about this

01:09:58.447 --> 01:10:01.145
result that didn't push up
compliance rates,

01:10:01.145 --> 01:10:04.784
how could we change the law or
change the incentives in the

01:10:04.784 --> 01:10:08.550
game so that it actually would
change compliance rates?

01:10:08.550 --> 01:10:14.090
What could we do?
Yeah.

01:10:14.090 --> 01:10:19.350
Student: If we changed
the payoffs of auditing to 4,

01:10:19.350 --> 01:10:22.390
from 2 to 4.
Professor Ben Polak:

01:10:22.390 --> 01:10:26.063
Good, if we want to change the
compliance rates we should

01:10:26.063 --> 01:10:28.489
change the payoffs to the
auditor.

01:10:28.489 --> 01:10:32.821
The problem with the way the
auditor is paid here is that the

01:10:32.821 --> 01:10:36.503
auditor is paid more if they
manage to catch people,

01:10:36.503 --> 01:10:39.581
but audits are costly.
The problem with that is when

01:10:39.581 --> 01:10:42.066
you raise the fine on the other
side, all that happens is the

01:10:42.066 --> 01:10:43.930
auditor's audit less often in
equilibrium.

01:10:43.930 --> 01:10:46.488
So if you want to get a higher
compliance rate,

01:10:46.488 --> 01:10:49.269
one thing you could do is
change the payoffs to the

01:10:49.269 --> 01:10:52.050
auditor to make auditing less
costly for them,

01:10:52.050 --> 01:10:56.069
or making catching people nicer
for them, give them a reward,

01:10:56.069 --> 01:11:00.090
or you could simply take it out
of Game Theory altogether.

01:11:00.090 --> 01:11:03.232
You could enforce,
you could have congressional

01:11:03.232 --> 01:11:06.989
law that sets the audit rates
outside of equilibrium,

01:11:06.989 --> 01:11:09.804
and that's been much discussed
in Congress over the last five

01:11:09.804 --> 01:11:11.550
years.
Somebody setting audit rates,

01:11:11.550 --> 01:11:13.300
as it were, exogenously by
Congress.

01:11:13.300 --> 01:11:15.199
Why might that not be a great
idea?

01:11:15.199 --> 01:11:17.908
Leaving aside Economic Theory
for a second,

01:11:17.908 --> 01:11:21.326
leaving aside Game Theory,
why might it not be a great

01:11:21.326 --> 01:11:25.001
idea to have Congress set the
audit rates rather than some

01:11:25.001 --> 01:11:27.154
office?
Student: Most members in

01:11:27.154 --> 01:11:29.824
Congress have a lot of money so
they're going to lower the audit

01:11:29.824 --> 01:11:31.520
rates so that they don't get
audited.

01:11:31.520 --> 01:11:33.454
Professor Ben Polak: So
the lady in the front is saying

01:11:33.454 --> 01:11:34.850
that a lot of Congressmen are
rather rich,

01:11:34.850 --> 01:11:36.329
so maybe they have particular
incentives here.

01:11:36.329 --> 01:11:39.205
I don't want to take a
particular political stance

01:11:39.205 --> 01:11:42.726
here, but it could be whatever
side of the political spectrum

01:11:42.726 --> 01:11:45.676
you guys sit on,
it could be that you might not

01:11:45.676 --> 01:11:47.689
trust Congress to get this
right.

01:11:47.689 --> 01:11:50.951
You might think they're going
to be political considerations

01:11:50.951 --> 01:11:54.212
going on in Congress other than
just having an efficient tax

01:11:54.212 --> 01:11:56.846
system.
Okay, so what do I want to draw

01:11:56.846 --> 01:12:00.082
out as lessons here?
The big lessons from this class

01:12:00.082 --> 01:12:02.965
are there are three different
ways to think about

01:12:02.965 --> 01:12:06.210
randomization in equilibrium or
out of equilibrium.

01:12:06.210 --> 01:12:08.099
One is it's genuinely
randomization,

01:12:08.099 --> 01:12:10.528
another is it could be
something about peoples

01:12:10.528 --> 01:12:12.920
belief's,
and a third way and a very

01:12:12.920 --> 01:12:16.692
important way is it could be
telling us something about the

01:12:16.692 --> 01:12:20.529
proportion of people who are
doing something in society,

01:12:20.529 --> 01:12:26.479
in this case the proportion of
people who are paying tax.

01:12:26.479 --> 01:12:29.605
A second important lesson I
want to draw out here,

01:12:29.605 --> 01:12:33.572
beyond just finding equilibria,
two other things we drew out

01:12:33.572 --> 01:12:37.229
today, one lesson was when
you're checking equilibria,

01:12:37.229 --> 01:12:41.089
checking mixed strategy
equilibria, you only have to

01:12:41.089 --> 01:12:43.890
check for pure strategy
deviations.

01:12:43.890 --> 01:12:47.023
Be careful, you have to check
for all possible pure strategy

01:12:47.023 --> 01:12:50.262
deviations, not just the pure
strategies that were involved in

01:12:50.262 --> 01:12:52.888
the mix.
If the guy has seven strategies

01:12:52.888 --> 01:12:56.415
and is only mixing on two,
you have to remember to check

01:12:56.415 --> 01:12:59.100
the other five.
The third lesson I want to draw

01:12:59.100 --> 01:13:01.569
out today is because of the way
equilibria works,

01:13:01.569 --> 01:13:06.717
mixed strategy equilibria work,
if I change the column player's

01:13:06.717 --> 01:13:11.199
payoffs it changes the row
player's equilibrium mix,

01:13:11.199 --> 01:13:14.215
and if I change the row
player's payoffs,

01:13:14.215 --> 01:13:17.909
it changes the column player's
equilibrium mix.

01:13:17.909 --> 01:13:20.939
Next time, we're going to pick
up this idea that mixed

01:13:20.939 --> 01:13:23.912
strategies can be about
proportions of people playing

01:13:23.912 --> 01:13:27.000
things and take it to a totally
different setting,

01:13:27.000 --> 01:13:30.432
namely evolution.
So on Wednesday we'll start

01:13:30.432 --> 01:13:32.098
talking about evolution.
 

